Return the subsequence of seq from start (inclusive) to end (exclusive) that is interned. What's different about this method from manually finding the subsequence and interning the subsequence is that if the subsequence is already interned, we can avoid having to compute the sequence. Since derived variables in Daikon compute the subsequence many times, this shortcut saves quite a bit of computation. It saves even more when there may be many derived variables that are non-canonical, since they are guaranteed to be ==.

Requires that seq is already interned.
